The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Bengal | Aila damage severe, says Delhi team
                                                                                                               Aila damage severe, says Delhi team
          OUR BUREAU                               
	Calcutta, June 9: The central team that completed its recce to assess the impact of Aila today said the devastation was severe and extensive.        
	The devastation was severe and extensive in some areas. Wed submit our report accordingly, said Asoke Lavasa, the Union home ministry joint secretary who led the team.        
	He wouldnt say whether it could be called a national disaster but state finance minister Asim Dasgupta said the tag was not essential to get money from the national calamity and contingency fund.        
	According to the 12th Finance Commission, this declaration (national disaster) isnt a pre-condition for funds. The thrust is on the word severe, Dasgupta said after a meeting with the central team, which came after he sought Rs 1,000 crore for relief from Delhi.         
	We told them Sunderbans had not witnessed such devastation in 100 years, he added.        
	The team declined to be drawn into any controversy over the states distribution of relief. We were not here to inves-tigate but to understand the suffering of the flood-hit. It is difficult to say if all the expectations of the people have been met, Lavasa said.        
	Chief minister Buddhadeb Bhattacharjee and CPM state secretary Biman Bose today iterated their appreciation of the role played by the Congress and Prime Minister Manmohan Singh after the calamity.        
	The Congress had attended an all-party meeting to discuss relief, though ally Trinamul Congress did not, signed a joint a resolution with the Bhattacharjee government underlining the need for Centre-state co-operation and agreed to attend the next round of talks.        
	Bhattacharjee told a front meeting he was in touch with the Prime Minister and finance minister Pranab Mukherjee and would meet them during his June 19 Delhi visit.                                                                                                                                                                             
